    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mommy Books: More Buzz Than Buyers'' (Arts pages, April 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mommy Books: More Buzz Than Buyers'' (Arts pages, April 25):</p>
        <p>Maybe the reason that ''mommy'' books don't sell in great quantity is that the subject is boring.</p>
        <p>If you stay at home with children, you're busy vacuuming, laundering, changing diapers and figuring out meal rotations (''We had chicken nuggets last night? Are you sure?''). The last thing you want to settle down with at the end of the day is a book about the inadequacies of your domestic life and how you could, would, should have a job that includes pay and recognition.</p>
        <p>Give me a break. Actually, give me Madame Bovary.</p>
        <p>Read about the ''dreariness'' of my domestic life or that of a fictional character? I'll take fiction any day of the week.</p>
        <p>Catherine Chatham  New York, April 26, 2007</p>
      </block>
